Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: United Bank, Nigerian Breweries Gain

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-04-18T15:48:19Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-18/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-united-bank-nigerian-breweries.html
The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-
Share Index rose for a fifth day, gaining 1.1 percent to
25,309.09 by the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according to an e-
mailed statement from the bourse, the longest winning streak
since Jan. 25.  Namibia’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  slumped 3.1 percent to
842.17 by the 4:00 p.m. close in Windhoek, the most since May
2010. The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index fell 0.4 percent
to 1,057.32 as of the 3:00 p.m. close in Accra. Kenya’s All-
Share Index climbed for the second day, adding 0.2 percent to
74.64 by the 3:00 p.m. close in Nairobi. Mauritius’s SEMDEX
Index dropped for a second day, falling 0.3 percent to 2,043.01
by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis .  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Nigerian Breweries Plc (NB)  , the second-largest stock by
weighting in the All-Share Index, gained 2.06 naira, or 2.4
percent, to 87.06 naira, the highest since Jan. 20, after saying
yesterday it’s in talks with parent company Heineken NV to buy
three breweries.  United Bank for Africa Plc (UBA)  ,  Nigeria ’s fifth-
largest lender by market value, advanced for a second day,
adding 12 kobo, or 1.5 percent, to 8.2 naira. The bank plans to
start operating in Malu and Republic of Congo, Phillips Oduoza,
UBA’s managing director, said on Johannesburg-based CNBC Africa
television today.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Chris Kay in London at 
